<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB031FB8BD87EFB69" box="[847,1126,1140,1166]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">Paltechioceras charpentieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
en raison de leur costulation forte, faite de côtes au relief bien marqué, à la fois proverses et légèrement arquées vers l’avant, s’infléchissant légèrement sur le bord externe en perdant de leur relief. Malgré les artéfacts dus à l’écrasement des coquilles, on peut observer que, comme chez cette espèce, la carène est nettement bordée par deux sillons.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A9A36561FF8AFFEBB053FA8BD84BF9CA" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="E10636EAFF8AFFEBB053FA8BDFB6FA6B" blockId="17.[811,1457,1396,1581]" box="[813,942,1396,1422]" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">DISCUSSION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E10636EAFF8AFFEBB053FA6BD84BF9CA" blockId="17.[811,1457,1396,1581]" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">
<taxonomicName id="26B94D69FF8AFFEBB053FA6BDFDDFA4A" authorityName="Schafhault" authorityYear="1847" baseAuthorityName="Schafhault" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[813,965,1427,1453]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Ammonoidea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Paltechioceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonitida" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="charpentieri">
<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB053FA6BDFDDFA4A" box="[813,965,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">P. charpentieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
est considéré par 
<bibRefCitation id="85284B1BFF8AFFEBB7EDFA6CD90FFA49" author="BLAU J." box="[1171,1303,1427,1454]" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" pagination="177 - 285" refId="ref17719" refString="BLAU J. 1998. - Monographie der Ammoniten des Obersinemurium (Lotharingium, Lias) der Lienzer Dolomiten (Osterreich): Biostratigraphie, Systematik and Palaobiogeographie. Revue de Paleobiologie 17 (1): 177 - 285." type="journal article" year="1998">Blau (1998)</bibRefCitation>
et 
<bibRefCitation id="85284B1BFF8AFFEBB641FA6CDFA5FA2A" author="MEISTER C. &amp; FRIEBE J. G." pageId="17" pageNumber="110" pagination="9 - 99" refId="ref20531" refString="MEISTER C. &amp; FRIEBE J. G. 2003. - Austroalpine Liassic Ammonites from Vorarlberg (Austria, Northern Calcareous Alps). Beitrage zur Palaontologie 28: 9 - 99." type="journal article" year="2003">Meister &amp; Friebe (2003)</bibRefCitation>
comme une espèce intermédiaire entre les deux genres 
<taxonomicName id="26B94D69FF8AFFEBB008FA2CD81AFA0A" authorityName="Buckman" authorityYear="1924" box="[886,1026,1491,1517]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Ammonoidea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Paltechioceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonitida" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB008FA2CD81AFA0A" box="[886,1026,1491,1517]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">Paltechioceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
et 
<taxonomicName id="26B94D69FF8AFFEBB75CFA2CD8ABFA0A" authorityName="Buckman" authorityYear="1923" box="[1058,1203,1491,1517]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Ammonoidea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Leptechioceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonitida" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB75CFA2CD8ABFA0A" box="[1058,1203,1491,1517]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">Leptechioceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. La présence des sillons péricarénaux permet de placer, sans ambiguïté, nos spécimens dans le genre 
<taxonomicName id="26B94D69FF8AFFEBB0C1F9EDD853F9CB" authorityName="Buckman" authorityYear="1924" box="[959,1099,1554,1580]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Ammonoidea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Paltechioceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonitida" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB0C1F9EDD853F9CB" box="[959,1099,1554,1580]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">Paltechioceras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A9A36561FF8AFFEBB053F9AED8C9F80C" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" type="description">
<paragraph id="E10636EAFF8AFFEBB053F9AED815F98B" blockId="17.[811,1457,1617,2027]" box="[813,1037,1617,1646]" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">ÂGE ET RÉPARTITION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E10636EAFF8AFFEBB053F98CD8C9F80C" blockId="17.[811,1457,1617,2027]" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">
<taxonomicName id="26B94D69FF8AFFEBB053F98CDFA5F96B" authorityName="Schafhault" authorityYear="1847" baseAuthorityName="Schafhault" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[813,957,1650,1676]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Ammonoidea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Paltechioceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonitida" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="charpentieri">
<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB053F98CDFA5F96B" box="[813,957,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">P. charpentieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
est surtout connu sur la marge nord de la Téthys (Austroalpin supérieur d’Autriche et de 
<collectingCountry id="99AE767AFF8AFFEBB79FF96DD958F94A" box="[1249,1344,1682,1709]" name="Hungary" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">Hongrie</collectingCountry>
), où il est récolté 
<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB004F94CDFA3F92B" box="[890,955,1715,1740]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">in situ</emphasis>
dans la partie inférieure de la sous-chronozone à Macdonnelli (Horizon à Meigeni-Charpentieri de 
<bibRefCitation id="85284B1BFF8AFFEBB61EF92DDFA0F8EB" author="BLAU J. &amp; MEISTER C." pageId="17" pageNumber="110" pagination="3 - 12" refId="ref17760" refString="BLAU J. &amp; MEISTER C. 2000. - Upper Sinemurian Ammonites Successions Based on 41 Faunal Horizons: an Attempt at Worldwide Correlation. GeoResearch Forum 6: 3 - 12." type="journal article" year="2000">Blau &amp; Meister 2000</bibRefCitation>
). Son âge est identique dans les confins méridionaux des plates-formes européennes (Pyrénées, Corbières). Il est très vraisemblable que le niveau stratigraphique de nos spécimens en soit très proche, comme il est très certainement très proche de celui de 
<taxonomicName id="26B94D69FF8AFFEBB75AF88DD8B3F86C" baseAuthorityName="Bose" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[1060,1195,1905,1931]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Ammonoidea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Paltechioceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonitida" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bavaricum">
<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB75AF88DD8B3F86C" box="[1060,1195,1905,1931]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">P. bavaricum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
avec lequel il est associé dans un contexte de vraisemblable condensation sédimentaire. 
<taxonomicName id="26B94D69FF8AFFEBB03FF84DDFCCF82C" authorityName="Schafhault" authorityYear="1847" baseAuthorityName="Schafhault" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[833,980,1969,1995]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Ammonoidea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Paltechioceras" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonitida" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="charpentieri">
<emphasis id="D3CDEAF8FF8AFFEBB03FF84DDFCCF82C" box="[833,980,1969,1995]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">P. charpentieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
est pour la première fois signalé sur la marge africaine de la Téthys méditerranéenne.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
